Views (Virtual tables)

	- A View is a virtual table created based on the result of a SQL query. 👁️

	- It does not store data physically — it only stores the query.

	- Whenever you access a view, MySQL runs the underlying query and shows the result.

	Simple: A view is a virtual table based on a SQL query that displays data from one or more tables without storing it physically.

	=> Example Table: employees

		| id | name  | department | salary |
		| -- | ----- | ---------- | ------ |
		| 1  | Ravi  | IT         | 50000  |
		| 2  | Priya | HR         | 45000  |
		| 3  | Arun  | IT         | 60000  |
		| 4  | Kiran | Finance    | 55000  |

	=> Example: Create a View

		Create a view for employees with salary > 50,000:

			CREATE VIEW high_salary_employees AS
			SELECT name, salary
			FROM employees
			WHERE salary > 50000;

		Using the View

			SELECT * FROM high_salary_employees;

		Result:

			| name  | salary |
			| ----- | ------ |
			| Arun  | 60000  |
			| Kiran | 55000  |

	=> Key Points About Views

		- View is a virtual table

		- It does not store actual data

		- It always shows latest data from base tables

		- Simplifies complex queries

	=> Example with Multiple Tables

		CREATE VIEW employee_department AS
		SELECT e.name, d.department_name
		FROM employees e
		JOIN departments d
		ON e.department_id = d.department_id;

		=> Now you can simply do:

			SELECT * FROM employee_department;

	=> Updating a View

		CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW high_salary_employees AS
		SELECT name, salary
		FROM employees
		WHERE salary > 55000;

	=> Dropping a View

		DROP VIEW high_salary_employees;

	=> Advantages of Views

		- Simplifies complex queries

		- Improves security (hide sensitive columns)

		- Reusable query logic

		- Shows only required data

	=> Disadvantages of Views

		- Performance can be slower (runs query each time)

		- Limited ability to update data

		- Depends on base tables

	=> Real Project Example

		- In an E-commerce system:

		- Instead of writing complex join queries every time:

			SELECT users.name, orders.order_id
			FROM users
			JOIN orders ON users.id = orders.user_id;

		- Create a view:

			CREATE VIEW user_orders AS ...

		- Now simply:

			SELECT * FROM user_orders;

	=> View vs Table

		| Feature     | View             | Table       |
		| ----------- | ---------------- | ----------- |
		| Storage     | No data stored   | Data stored |
		| Type        | Virtual          | Physical    |
		| Performance | Slower           | Faster      |
		| Usage       | Simplify queries | Store data  |

	=> Best Interview Answer (Short)

		- A view is a virtual table based on a SQL query that does not store data physically but displays data from one or more tables.

